Package io.artframework.parser

Class LineParser<TResult>

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.artframework.parser.LineParser<TResult>
  • Type Parameters:
    TResult - the result type of the parser
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.util.Iterator<java.lang.String>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    FlowLineParser
    public abstract class LineParser<TResult>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.Iterator<java.lang.String>
    Use the line parser as a super class for any parser class that processes a single line.

    A new line parser instance should be created for each iterator and use the same iterator reference. The line parser itself will not use the iterator to move the match forward. It is just used for downstream parsers that want to do forward parsing.

    accept(String) should be called with the Iterator.next() method to avoid a desynchronization of the iterator.

    Every line that is passed to the accept(String) method is pushed into the inputs() stack and provided a matcher() that is also pushed onto the matchers() stack. The matchers and inputs stacks are always in sync containing the same line.

    The stacks will not update if the provided input string is null or empty.

    See the FlowLineParser for an example implementation.

    Implementation Notice

    Make sure to use the next() method to get the next line in the iterator when doing forward lookups and multiline parsing.

        public final boolean accept​(java.lang.String line)
        Takes the given line and matches it against the given pattern.

        The line and the corresponding matcher will be pushed onto the stack. The last line and its matcher is always avaiable with the matcher() and input() method.
